bug.short_desc: VersionedIdentifier treats all feature versions as identical

long_desc.thetext:
I am attempting to install MyEclipse 5.0.1GA from an update site into an Eclipse configuration for which I have already installed all the Callisto features. I end up getting "Duplicate feature" errors in the error log as a result. The errors are triggered as a result of MyEclipse relying on earlier versions of some Callisto features. In addition, when I looked at the configuration manager, it showed later versions of features disabled and earlier versions enabled.
Tracing the error message to its source, I found it was generated by addFeatureEntry() in org/eclipse/update/internal/configurator/SiteEntry. Adding some trace I found that the compareVersion() method of VersionIdentifier was always returning EQUAL even when feature versions were different.
Internally, VersionedIdentifier has separate fields for major/minor/service/qualifier and uses these in comparisons. However, between 3.1 and 3.2, the code in the class constructor to initialise these fields was commented out. As a result, compareVersion() is always working on default values and hence always returns EQUAL.
I uncommented the routine to parse the version string into its components, and added a call to it in the constructor.
Rerunning the installation of MyEclipse above now resulted in no errors in the log and a correct looking configuration.
I'm happy to be corrected, but it looks like VersionedIdentifier should initialise its internal fields in its constructor.

bug.short_desc: Changing AspectJ compiler preferences results in erroneous classpath error on Java project

long_desc.thetext:
To recreate:
1. Create a single Java project in the workspace, with a single Java class in it.
2. Change a compiler preference at:
Window -> Preferences -> AspectJ Compiler
such as:
"Unknown absolute type name in pointcut:"
from "Ignore" to "Warning".
3. Click "Apply".
4. At the "Compiler Settings Changed" prompt, click "Yes" to start the full build.
An "AJDT Internal Error" dialog appears with the message "An error occurred while building. Check the error log (via Window > Show View > Error Log) for details."
The "Problems" view will show the error "classpath error: unable to find org.aspectj.lang.JoinPoint (check that aspectjrt.jar is in your classpath)"
The "Error Log" will show the warning "java.lang.NullPointerException encountered while running AspectJ Builder." with the stack trace:
java.lang.NullPointerException at org.eclipse.ajdt.internal.ui.markers.MarkerUpdating.addNewMarkers(MarkerUpdating.java:92) at org.eclipse.ajdt.internal.builder.UIBuildListener.postAJBuild(UIBuildListener.java:178) at org.eclipse.ajdt.core.builder.AJBuilder.postCallListeners(AJBuilder.java:843) at org.eclipse.ajdt.core.builder.AJBuilder.build(AJBuilder.java:285) at org.eclipse.core.internal.events.BuildManager$2.run(BuildManager.java:603) at org.eclipse.core.runtime.SafeRunner.run(SafeRunner.java:37) at org.eclipse.core.internal.events.BuildManager.basicBuild(BuildManager.java:167) at org.eclipse.core.internal.events.BuildManager.build(BuildManager.java:332) at org.eclipse.core.internal.resources.Project.build(Project.java:119) at org.eclipse.ajdt.internal.ui.preferences.PreferencePageBuilder$2.run(PreferencePageBuilder.aj:525) at org.eclipse.jface.operation.ModalContext$ModalContextThread.run(ModalContext.java:113)
and another warning: "Errors running builder "AspectJ Builder" on project SomeJavaLibrary." where "SomeJavaLibrary" is the name of your Java project.
There is also an error: "Problems occurred when invoking code from plug-in: "org.eclipse.core.resources". With the same stack trace as above.
Converting the Java project to an AspectJ project resolves this problem.

This is nasty, changing AJ settings shouldn't affect plain Java projects.
A guard against the NPE wouldn't hurt, but the underlying problem is that when global AJ compiler settings are changed we rebuild all projects, and we specifically invoke the AJ builder on all those projects. So the AJ builder is used for projects that wouldn't normally use it. Instead we should just call the version of build() that runs the builders associated with each project.
Fixed in: 1.4.1.200610271301 for Eclipse 3.2 (build.222) 1.5.0.200610271535 for Eclipse 3.3M2 (build.60)

I'd like to have change the PDOMBinding subclass constructors work only from a corresponding IBinding rather than look at the AST. The motivations are
(1) For adding a binding to a pdom that mirrors a binding in another pdom (offline/composite indexes) (2) For allowing out-of-order name addition to the PDOM. (This is where names from a source file are added /before/ names from a header included at the start of the source TU)

This patch is enough to partially address out-of-order name addition to the pdom. You can divide out-of-order name addition in to two parts (i) out-of-order within a contributing-part of a translation unit (i.e. dividing the final TU into its source and header parts) (ii) out-of-order between contributing-parts (but in AST occurrence order within the contributing-parts)
This patch fixes (ii). For example, previously when a reference to a resolved function was used as the basis of constructing a PDOMCPPFunction object, since the AST context was not a declaration, parameter information was skipped. bug.short_desc: Events are sent to ecftcp://localhost:4700/ .

long_desc.thetext:
Events are sent to ecftcp://localhost:4700/ . It need to be parametrized otherwise we cannot make a remote accessibility.
I think the best solution is to set the URI in PC definition as an additional repository.

FYI... The definition of a Project Context Container has a repository configuration for each RemoteEventRouter. Within this definition, the setting for using ECF for collaboration events is already parameterized.
The following is from the "CoronaDemo" context container. Note the use of "ecftcp://localhost:4700" is a configuration parameter.
<repository-configuration name="DefaultEventRouter"> <repository-connection-parameters access-type="http://www.eclipse.org/corona/accessTypes/ECFTCP" name="EventRouterECF"> <repository-connection-parameter name="uri" value="ecftcp://localhost:47000"/> </repository-connection-parameters> </repository-configuration>

It turned out that in fact the repository configuration is used in event factory, but later on the value of remote.uri was overwritten and the settings were not used.
Additionally if the event router is not defined, a warning is displayed during PC open. This should prevent from problems when events are not propagated.

Cross post from dev list:
The EventRouter method handleEvent calls the suppressSend method which looks at a list of remote EventRouter uris and decides whether to really publish the Collaboration Event. The list of remote EventRouter uris is placed into the CollaborationEvent (ProjectEvent) by the ProjectEventFactory and it uses information in the ProjectContextContainer to set the remote EventRouter uris but if your container doesnt have any uris listed no CollaborationEvent (ProjectEvent) will be sent. I think we should always send to the default EventRouter uri and if remote EventRouter uris are specified also send to them. Im not sure how someone creating a ProjectContextContainer is supposed to know to set the remote EventRouter uri to get CollaborationEvents sent.
Is there an easy way to determine the default EventRouter for User or a ProjectContextContainer? Im not sure I want the ProjectEventFactory to set the default EventRouter. It seems like the client EventRouter should have a way to find and set the default remote EventRouter uri
Comments?
Glenn Everitt

Recently I have added a validation when PC is opened. When you open a PC and there is no event router defined, there is an error message displayed saying that the PC definition is missing the event router and the collaboration events won't work. So, people will be aware that if they do not have event router defined, it won't work!
The two more possible solutions could be: 1. send to the same server where the PC definition is, but to port 4700. 2. add a configuration property with default router
But I think the best solution is to say that event router definition is required.

I think there is also one more posibility. Far I remember ECF has zeroconf implementation. It is a protocol to discover services in a network - http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zeroconf. I'm not sure, but I think it works only in local networks, because it seems that it is possible to discover services only through broadcast or multicast packages.
I tried to use it once to setup distcc (distributed C compiler) in Gdansk lab, so that the compilation claster would be set up dynamically, depending on who is online. I had a prototype but I never finished due to lack of time. But it worked - it was able to find distcc servers automatically.

I'm having trouble getting it to work using java web start, setting the properties in the jnlp file, but that is not an SWT issue obviously.

The basic problem can be solved by setting environment variables.
However, running from Java Web Start is a problem because generally the whole point of JWS is that it takes the place of an install. Requiring a user to set an environment variable or set something in their java control panel before running the program - well, it simply isn't very scalable if you have lots of users who want the easy web start install.
So I believe it can be made to work with JWS if the user sets the variable themselves somewhere. But it does not appear to be possible in the jnlp, because if you specify <property name="awt.toolkit" value="sun.awt.X11.XToolkit" /> it will set the property, but only after it is too late. Looking at the jnlp spec, it does not guarantee that the system properties will be set at jvm startup - it only guarantees that it is before your main executes. And if you look at your call stacks when running from JWS, you'll see why this is true: the JWS launcher itself uses java, so the JVM is already started well before any of your code is executed.
That said, I'd like to reopen this bug, not because it is necessarily the responsibility of the SWT team (it seems like some of the other SWT/AWT issues, it is a combination of SWT issues and Java issues), but because, simply put, it is still a problem. bug.short_desc: [multi monitor] Notification window appears on wrong monitor

long_desc.thetext: I have a 3 monitor system. Eclipse is running on the default monitor (where the Windows systray is), which happens to be the one in the middle. I'd expect the Mylar task change notification window to come up on my middle monitor but it's coming up on my right-most monitor.

I have the same problem when working with my home monitor configuration, and I simply miss the notifications because they're too far to see. When programming, many of us think of our Eclipse Workbench window as a desktop, so what I propose we do is make the notifications pop up on the low-right corner of the workbench window.
Rob: I took a quick crack at this but getting the client area from the workbench Window seems to return the wrong thing at times. I recall you having a problem with this way back, could you take a look? The bit of code I added to restoreBounds is commented out.
Created an attachment (id=52800) mylar/context/zip

I think somewhere on the current monitor (the display where the main Eclipse workbench window is) would be good, but not necessarily right on top of the workbench where stuff would be obscured. It would also be "nice to have" a feature like in MS Outlook where you can move the notification window when one comes up, and the next one will come up in the new place. I'm not sure if Gmail notifier can do that or not since I just left it on the bottom right.
Or, this might be a possible place to use a systray item and balloon.
If there are no multi-platform issues I'd be inclined to investigate the systray/balloon option.

The good thing about the system tray icon is that it builds in some consistency for free. But I have two qualms about it: 1) Some might get annoyed by the addition of yet another system tray icon. The system tray is overloaded on many users' machines that I have seen, especially by icons that alwyas claim to be active (e.g. preventing Windows from hiding them). I personally force a bunch of system tray icons to be hidden. 2) We need to be able to display images and formatted text to graphically indicate what icons changed. I've never seen a Windows balloon do this, is it possible?
Rob: please investigate (2).
Ed: what's your opinion on (1)? Notably Outlook only uses the icon to indicate that there is some new content, and uses a custom toaster widget for the notifications themselves. We could consider the same scheme? The option to move and remember the moved location is a good idea as you suggest, and we just have to make sure that we go back to the default if the display area changes to exclude those coordinates.

Most applications use the systray icon as a proxy for the main window. For example I have a systray icon for Google Desktop and one for Office Communicator, neither of which has a main window open. Are the notifications intended mainly for when the Eclipse window is open or not? (I think, probably open). Do they continue after you close the Eclipse window? (I think, probably not). So I'm leaning away from the systray idea. Sometimes though it's quicker to just try something out a few different ways to see if you like it or not, whether than spend too much time thinking on it. :)

I'm also leaning away from the systray idea for the same reasons, and yes we currently only show them when the Eclipse window is open (although they also show when the window is minimized).
Postponing with other multi monitor related fixes to our custom shells (bug 166990).

By the way, this notification is currently "always on top" and with its size it is quite annoying when it comes out of nowhere while you are in some other application. Also, when you have multiple Eclipse instances, you can't tell what instance that notification came from.

Created an attachment (id=62446) Mylar Notifications Patch
This patch will pop up notifications on the monitor of the active workbench window. If there is no active workbench window, then notifications will default to the primary monitor.
Excellent! Would this also address bug 166990?
Bug 166990 can probably be fixed by getting the bounds of the active window's monitor, confirming that tooltip.x + tooltip.width > monitor.x + monitor.width, and then repositioning tooltip.
Excellent! Patch applied, ip log updated. Lets watch notification width, may need to make default width wider.

bug.short_desc: How to handle dependency on JDT?

long_desc.thetext: With the addtion of org.eclipse.datatools.connectivity.jdt to the build, a dependency on the JDT is introduced. We don't want to make the JDT a requirement for running DTP, since only a small subset of plug-ins are ever likely to depend on it. Short of creating a separate feature only for this one plug-in, we should look at ways for the plug-in to gracefully fail to load if the JDT is not present. I believe there are some ways that you can express dependency contraints in the manifest to achieve this.

Any ideas on how I should handle this? I can make the JDT plugins optional dependencies and then check in the activator as to whether they're loaded. If they're not loaded, I can make a static flag in the activator that I check somehow when loading the wizard page for the classpath container?
Isn't this kind of a moot point though? If the JDT isn't loaded, t;he extensions won't be loaded and the user won't have the ability to configure a build path for a Java project.

I'm not really sure, but I think there are some options here. We'll need to put a JDT dependency somewhere in the feature definitions, since that is expected. But ideally, we'd like that dependency to be optional, so people can choose not to install the JDT and (again ideally), not receive error messages that the connectivity.jdt plug-in could not be loaded.

bug.short_desc: disable bootdelegation * by default

long_desc.thetext:
Equinox currently runs with the org.osgi.framework.bootdelegation set to * by default. This has been the default to support backwards compatibility for bundles which expect to get access to all classes available from the VM boot classpath (javax.xml.parsers, org.wc3.sax etc.).
There are two main reasons this is not a good default.
1) Performance
When we delegate every class load to the boot classloader we end up with tons of ClassNotFoundExceptions because we ask the boot classloader for everything even though we know the classes should come from another bundle. For example, we delegate every org.eclipse.* class. Measurements show bootdelegation is taking up to 5-7% of startup time to get to the JDK perspective.
2) Isolation
Delegating every class load to boot does not allow for us to isolate bundles from packages provided from the VM. This prevents us from shipping and using our own versions of the packages in bundles.
-------------------------------------------------
Proposed solution:
- By default we would not set the org.osgi.framework.bootdelegation to anything (today it is set to "*").
- We would add a new option that would enable a "boot" buddy policy for every bundle in the framework. This new option would be enabled by default in Equinox.
This adds a last resort boot delegation to the end of the OSGi delegation model. Delegation to boot would occur after asking the bundle's dependencies (Import-Package, Require-Bundle) and local classloader for the class.
The advantage to this approach is that it provides the performance improvements and isolation we want but it provides a level of compatibility for bundles which are expecting to get stuff from boot for free.
---------------------------------------------------------------
Issues
Tooling: We need help from PDE to flag warnings to developers that are accessing packages from the VM without specifying proper dependencies in their bundle manifests.
Compatibility: Some bundles today include packages that are provided by the executing VM. For example, some bundles include their own versions of javax.xml.parsers package. With bootdelegation * these types of bundles are not actually loading classes from these packages, instead they are getting the classes provided by the VM. This is probably not not the behavior developers were expecting.
With the proposed changes these types of bundles will now be able to load and use the classes they include in themselves because we will ask their classloader for the class before asking boot. This is probably more like the behavior the developer is expecting but it does add more burden to such a bundle because now we will have multiple versions of the same package available in the framework.

>We need help from PDE to flag warnings to developers that are accessing >packages from the VM without specifying proper dependencies in their bundle >manifests.
I am not sure what PDE can do here.
1. We cannot flag anything on Java files. that's the compiler's job. We only flag things on manifest files, which, in this case, are fine.
2. PDE does not own the JRE container, so we cannot put access rules on the JRE packages.

There is no way we can get the JRE container to allow PDE to contribute access rules? If we could do this then I would want you to add discouraged access rules to packages that are not imported from the VM.
If that is not possible then some kind of warning would be useful on the manifest. But I'm not sure how you would detect the error condition without a access rule to flag the error at compile time. Are you going to do the class analysis your self to see what packages are access from the VM?

I thought we had something that detected when you were using packages you did not have a dependency on? When using the secondary classpath all manner of things will compile but the bundle will not run if the dependency is not stated. I vaguely recall that there may have been some performance or integration issues related to adding real time feedback support. If you use the manifest clean up (actually the "add dependencies" link on the manifest dependencies page you do get the javax.* dependencies added if they are used in your code.
So essentially this usecase spawns another request to have dynamic feedback when you are using packages (any packages) that are not available by the curent dependencies

Essentially, the problem boils down to the following: We don't want plug-ins to get free access to the non-java.* packages from the JRE container at development time. We want them to account for these packages via Import-Package (or Require-Bundle ;-).
Right now, non-java.* packages are legitimately getting on the classpath via the JRE container, which PDE does not have control over.
>There is no way we can get the JRE container to allow PDE to contribute access >rules? If we could do this then I would want you to add discouraged access >rules to packages that are not imported from the VM.
This is currently not possible. However, I think this may be the only clean solution. Perhaps the EE analyzer that classifies JREs/EEs for JDT can also return an array of access rules, given an EE-based JRE.
Incidentally, we have discussed the possibility of having access rules on JRE containers many times in the past. For some reason, Jeff has always been against it, but I am not sure the reason was very compelling. I believe it had to do with the fact that differences between J2SE-1.3 and J2SE-1.4, for example, cannot be accurately captured on a package-level granularity. That's a fair point, but having access rules at a package level is better than nothing

Wassim, Wassim, Wassim. Comment 3 didn't say anything about access rules. You just have them stuck in your brain. Indeed having JRE access rules would be interesting for the same reason that having them for normal bundle-bundle releationships is interesting -- they make explicit the dependency relationships.
JRE access rules are mildly interesting for the case you cite in an accusatorial tone. Here you have a bundle that states it needs 1.3 but you have only 1.4. Using JRE access rules to filter the 1.4 so it looks like 1.3 gets you part way there but leaves lots of holes. People are better off just getting a real 1.3. IMHO.
But enough about access rules! Comment 3 focuses on the secondary dependency mechanims we already have. It works splendidly except that developers need to know that they should hit the "add dependencies" link. Apparently that checks will be run on launch as well but that is very disconnected from the acutal process of developing the code. The suggestion here is that the detection happen automatically and a warning appear on the manifest saying something like "The code in this bundle references Java packages that do not appear in any dependencies" with a quickfix that basically runs the add dependencies function. I belive that this would address the concerns in this bug.

I did realize comment 3 was not about access rules. I was just concurring with comment 2 that access rules may be the way to go. In the process, I started quoting people "accurately", but slightly out of context. Ask Chris A, a little slander never hurt anyone :)
I don't think our solution should be centered around 'automated management of dependencies', aka. secondary dependencies, since not everybody uses that support.
What comment 3 and comment 5 suggest are good ideas though that could complement access rules to provide a nice overall story.

Created an attachment (id=53650) patch
This patch adds the last resort boot delegation for compatibility. For now I added an option to enable this "osgi.compatibility.bootdelegation". The EclipseAdaptorHook enables this option by default unless it is already set to true or false (in the config.ini, using -D vm arg etc.). The org.osgi.framework.bootdelegation property is no longer set to "*" by default.
We need to decide if this is option (osgi.compatibility.bootdelegation) is ok. For now I will release this patch so we can make progress and to see if this approach is feasible.

I have a solution that seems to work for removing objects from the DSE if they're not appropriate for a given profile type (i.e. Hypersonic DB doesn't have Stored Procedures). After discussing this with Loic, it appears we may insert some additional support cues in the DB definition to help make this easier.

JDBCCatalog JDBCDatabase JDBCCatalogLoader JDBCSchema JDBCSchemaLoader
And then provide a navigator content extension that's basically a duplicate of what's in *.sqm.server.ui for SQL Model Content and provide my updated pipeline content provider.

bug.short_desc: Cannot access features whose names clash with pre-defined iterators

long_desc.thetext:
The OCL parser cannot parse feature calls where the feature in question has the same name as one of the OCL pre-defined iterators. For example, in the UML2 metamodel, MultiplicityElements have an 'isUnique' property. Expressions such as
self.isUnique
result in parse failures:
'token "isUnique is invalid"'
The reason for this is that the grammar definition identifies these iterator names as 'keywords', a consequence of which is that they are not valid identifiers (for types, features, etc.). This should not be a problem, as iteration expressions require the arrow operator "->" to distinguish them from feature calls.

This is also a problem in the case of features whose names coincide with other tokens defined by the parser grammar as 'keywords', such as 'body':
package ocl::uml context Constraint inv: self.body.name <> 'foo' endpackage

Committed a fix, for the specific cases of pre-defined iterator names (isUnique, select, reject, etc.) and certain other names including: package, context, body.
This problem should be revisited in the next release to find a way in the LPG grammar to do without requiring "keywords" in the rules for iterators.
